How true is the saying "The smarter you get the less you speak"?

My younger sister is undeniably smart.

She reads obsessively.

She even skipped a grade.

Usually, she doesn't speak unless spoken to.

She's definitely an introvert but is loved by all.

But you introduce anything thought-provoking, and her mouth won't shut.

Her brain fires a thousand billion synapses.

She has to speak before her thoughts get too loud.

The only reason you think smart people are quiet is because you don't have interesting conversations with them.

Smart people are never quiet when you make them think.

What a bummer.

Edit: For those who asked, here’s another answer about her: When did you realize small things matter?

Can you tell me something inspiring?

I stopped writing on Quora.

I find that inspiring because I wasn’t the happiest person I was when I was writing here.

I would write about existential crises.

And people liked it.

But it’s been months.

I haven’t written on Quora.

Because all that writing has gone into a book.

So if you ever pass by your nearest bookstore and flip open a book about a girl named Lucy who’s going through an existential crisis, I guess you’ll know who wrote it.

What are you afraid of and why?

I'm afraid that my goals are just a distraction from reality.

I'm afraid that I read books because they make me escape reality.

And I'm afraid that it's not just books, but that one day,

It'll become my job and my family and my art and everything I care about.

Distractions and escapes from the fact that our existence is random and meaningless and bound to cease.

But I guess fear was always meant for the things we'll never answer.

Why do we even get attached to people? What’s the point?
Originally Answered: Why do we even grow attached to people, what's the point?

Fake flowers cost less than real ones, despite lasting forever.

There is a price to that life within the real flowers.

Fake flowers will give you an eternity throughout your life.

Real flowers will give you an eternity thoughout their lives.

Only people can make you feel infinite in the tiniest moments throughout your life, and these end up to be your most beautiful memories.

There is beauty in eternity only if it ends.

Otherwise, it's a curse.

Are most people on Quora lonely?

A few may have realized that I've taken a break from Quora.

And it was mainly because, instead of having a conversation with the people around me, I was writing here.

It helps with my writing and I met great people.

But it really doesn't make me any better with real people.

Ever since I took that break, I've made more friends and actually began working at my sport and finished my book. I've become healthier in every way.

Not every Quoran is a lone Wolf. But after a while, if you don't limit yourself, I promise you…

You're going to become one.

What is the saddest thing you've ever seen?

The saddest thing I'd ever seen was the hope in a family's tearful eyes the moment before their father died.

He was the first person I saw die.

I remember how grey his face was.

How he sounded like he was howling for help when breathing through his air mask.

And when he looked in his wife's eyes, all he could see is the pain he promised to protect her from.

For that, his spirit was crushed.

With all the wealth and authority he earned, what use is power when you can't save the people you love?”

Can you get 0 upvotes to save your life?

The truth is, you don't know what 0 is.

Imagine a red car traveling slowly. You can see it clearly.

Now it's traveling very fast, it becomes a red blur.

But if the car reached the speed of light, it travels so fast that… You no longer see it.

The car exists at every moment in spacetime that it has become infinite. And at the same time, it has disappeared.

So basically, 0 and infinity are no different.

And you are asking me if I can get an infinite number of upvotes. But Quora has only a 100 million active users.

So my answer is.

Not Yet.

What's the nicest thing anyone has ever done for you?

My grandma's been sleeping over in our house, and she sleeps in my bed.

Every morning for the past week, I go back to my room to study and find my bed military-style done.

By whom?

My grandmother struggling with obesity, can barely move without her cane, and has to put on an oxygen mask for the slightest amount of work done.

It was then that I knew, broken people are the nicest.
